## 3. Physics-Informed Neural Network (PINN)

To address the physical non-compliance of the MLP, we introduce a PINN. The network $N_\theta(t)$ is trained not just on the data, but is penalized if its derivatives violate the Lorenz equations. 

The physics-informed residual loss is defined as:

$$
\mathcal{L}_{physics} = \left\| \frac{d\hat{x}}{dt} - \sigma(\hat{y} - \hat{x}) \right\|^2 + \left\| \frac{d\hat{y}}{dt} - (\hat{x}(\rho - \hat{z}) - \hat{y}) \right\|^2 + \left\| \frac{d\hat{z}}{dt} - (\hat{x}\hat{y} - \beta \hat{z}) \right\|^2
$$

While PINNs excel at interpolation (learning the training region), chaotic systems present a severe challenge for extrapolation due to extreme stiffness and gradient pathologies during optimization.

